New Reorganization of the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the US State Department, explains his,,Roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and what the Iraqi people, with the help of the Americans, can now place on its feet in particular - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
A open, market-oriented and peaceful Iraq could provide reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take its time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the Middle East have been grasped.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning of the Americans and the whole world and thanks to the rapid, concentrated, and targeted intervention of the coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is smaller than assumed.
There is a need for humanitarian aid here and there, but fortunately the massive crisis announced never came to pass.
There are relatively few refugees and displaced persons within Iraq. The supply of food, water, and medicine is adequate in most cases, or at least improving.
The American government has made about 600 million dollars available through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
We also need to restore the basic order in Iraq.
Safety is the indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without safety, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work or schools.
After the fall of Saddam, a wave of plundering, lawlessness and settling of scores followed.
Now it is the top priority to put an end to this violence.
In addition, it should be the task of international troops to ensure and eliminate all mass destruction weapons, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors further worsen the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures, so that they can take care of their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be considered more precisely as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of raw materials to process in Iraq.
The US provides more than 2 billion dollars in support for the initial reconstruction efforts.
The oil production is raised to a better level.
Among the long-term challenges are an increase in oil production and the reduction of Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision of the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome in this context.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographical, and political chasms in Iraqi society, the help with the political renewal of Iraq is probably the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq where the law is respected and the government comes into being democratically - is not a castle in the air, especially not because Iraq has an educated population and a rather large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue on the course taken and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported, so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly an external policy issue that has occupied and polarized public opinion as strongly as the Palestinian question.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the US developed a roadmap that brings us closer to this goal in stages.
A new Palestinian government and the new Prime Minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to start this process and take measures to improve the situation, so that afterwards broader topics can be taken up at the negotiating table.
Ultimately, it cannot be acceptable that terrorists ruin the peace process for all time.
But a solution to the Palestinian question is not automatically also the solution to all problems of the Middle East.
Clear and obvious are the challenges that Iran presents to us. This country is developing mass destruction weapons and has supported terrorism.
Their behavior spits on the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues on this path, there will be consequences.
However, if one refrains from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the USA is ready to re-establish good relations with this country.
Similarly, the USA is ready to approach Syria if substantial changes in attitudes are made.
A rather general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
America for too long tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to intervene in a representative government form.
We have painfully felt that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the USA, the West, and the world.
That's why we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, which was launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
The countries in the Middle East, as shown by the previous year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), remained far behind other regions in terms of personal freedom, women's rights, and economic and social development.
They had to watch for too long as the economic upswing passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If one were to implement within a decade the recently proposed plan of a free trade zone between the US and the Middle East, it would be a sustainable basis for such development.
